Well, am I invited
to the wedding?

489
00:43:05,813 --> 00:43:07,075
I'll ask Roy.

490
00:43:12,686 --> 00:43:15,120
Yeah, it's pretty good
in this precinct.

491
00:43:15,189 --> 00:43:17,123
Here you go.

492
00:43:17,191 --> 00:43:21,093
Usually a 9:00 to 5:00 day is the
best time for policy and bookmaking.

493
00:43:22,029 --> 00:43:25,556
If you have to work nights, like
a liquor violation, just call in.

494
00:43:25,633 --> 00:43:27,999
Don't worry about
quotas right now.

495
00:43:28,069 --> 00:43:31,197
Couple of hooker collars
will keep it cool.

496
00:43:42,316 --> 00:43:44,409
Been holding this for you.

497
00:43:44,485 --> 00:43:46,953
It's from Jewish Max.

498
00:44:42,910 --> 00:44:45,401
First day on the precinct,
I get that.

499
00:44:48,182 --> 00:44:50,116
This is great, Frank.

500
00:44:52,920 --> 00:44:55,013
I can open up a whole can
of peas with this.

501
00:44:55,089 --> 00:44:56,681
It's scary.

502
00:44:57,892 --> 00:45:00,588
I wanna protect myself.

503
00:45:00,661 --> 00:45:02,856
- You know what we do with this?
- What?

504
00:45:02,930 --> 00:45:05,524
We take it to
Inspector Kellogg.

505
00:45:10,838 --> 00:45:14,239
Kellogg... Didn't he used
to be in plainclothes?

506
00:45:14,308 --> 00:45:17,869
He's the second-highest ranking cop
in the department of investigations.

507
00:45:17,945 --> 00:45:20,243
- So what?
- What do you mean, "so what?"

508
00:45:20,314 --> 00:45:22,578
I happened to be instrumental
in getting the man his job.

509
00:45:22,650 --> 00:45:24,743
He owes me.
You understand?

510
00:45:25,986 --> 00:45:28,250
He's the most honest cop
I know, Frank.

511
00:45:29,623 --> 00:45:32,888
Frank, trust me.

512
00:45:44,705 --> 00:45:49,404
Things like this were common
practice in the bad old days.

513
00:45:49,476 --> 00:45:51,740
Hard to believe
it's still going on.

514
00:45:55,449 --> 00:45:58,111
Serpico, don't you think
it's kind of stupid...

515
00:45:58,185 --> 00:46:01,018
taking an envelope from somebody
you didn't know?

516
00:46:06,126 --> 00:46:09,289
What was I supposed to do?
I mean, give me...

517
00:46:09,363 --> 00:46:12,526
How would I know what was in it
unless I took it?

518
00:46:12,600 --> 00:46:15,125
You have two alternatives.

519
00:46:15,202 --> 00:46:18,569
You can force me to take you to
the commissioner of investigations.

520
00:46:18,639 --> 00:46:20,903
He'll drag you in front
of a grand jury.

521
00:46:20,975 --> 00:46:24,433
- I don't want that.
- I can understand that.

522
00:46:24,511 --> 00:46:26,445
Word will get out.

523
00:46:26,513 --> 00:46:30,449
Before it's all over, they'll find
you face-down in the East River.

524
00:46:36,090 --> 00:46:39,491
- What's the other alternative?
- Forget it.

525
00:46:41,562 --> 00:46:43,826
Well, what do I do with this?

526
00:47:06,086 --> 00:47:08,213
Hey, Sarge?
You got a minute?

527
00:47:11,725 --> 00:47:14,694
Colored cop gave me this.
I didn't know what to do with it.

528
00:47:21,001 --> 00:47:23,834
Well, I'll send it on
to the Benevolent Association.

529
00:47:35,616 --> 00:47:37,550
Alfie, come on.

530
00:47:59,273 --> 00:48:01,207
Is that Bjoerling?

531
00:48:07,648 --> 00:48:09,582
No. It's DiStefano.

532
00:48:11,785 --> 00:48:14,379
I was sure it was Bjoerling.

533
00:48:21,495 --> 00:48:24,157
You could hear it
better over here.

534
00:48:25,065 --> 00:48:27,226
- That's an invitation, right?
- Right.

535
00:48:28,369 --> 00:48:29,836
For coffee.

536
00:48:30,904 --> 00:48:34,601
I'll have to take a rain check.
I'm due at the hospital.

537
00:48:34,675 --> 00:48:37,803
Why don't you call in sick?
Perfect place.

538
00:48:39,613 --> 00:48:40,807
Not me.

539
00:48:40,881 --> 00:48:43,145
What are you,
dedicated or somethin'?

540
00:48:43,217 --> 00:48:47,916
That's right, I'm dedicated.
Most men can't stand it.

541
00:48:47,988 --> 00:48:51,287
- Well, what do they know?
- I like your garden.

542
00:48:57,398 --> 00:48:58,831
Love my garden.

543
00:49:00,167 --> 00:49:02,863
Okay. I love your garden.

544
00:49:04,338 --> 00:49:06,272
You know what they say,
don't you?

545
00:49:07,574 --> 00:49:09,166
No. What do they say?

546
00:49:09,810 --> 00:49:13,337
If you love a man's garden,
you gotta love the man.

547
00:49:19,787 --> 00:49:21,721
You like her, Alfie?

548
00:49:23,257 --> 00:49:25,919
All I can tell you, sir,
is I gave it back.

549
00:49:25,993 --> 00:49:28,393
I gotta get out of the 93.

550
00:49:28,462 --> 00:49:31,795
Well, what happened on
your narcotics application?

551
00:49:31,866 --> 00:49:35,825
Looked like it was set, until
I told 'em I was in plainclothes.

552
00:49:35,903 --> 00:49:37,700
It was like
the kiss of death.

553
00:49:37,772 --> 00:49:41,037
They think everybody in clothes
is on the take.

554
00:49:41,108 --> 00:49:43,770
Sir, do you know anything about
the Bronx 7th Division?

555
00:49:43,844 --> 00:49:47,803
I can go there if I want,
but if it's the same shit, screw it.

556
00:49:47,882 --> 00:49:51,374
I'd rather answer phones for Spanish
communications unit and go nuts.

557
00:49:51,452 --> 00:49:53,044
Come on, Alfie.

558
00:49:54,755 --> 00:49:57,747
Frank, did anyone
ever tell you...

559
00:49:57,825 --> 00:50:00,419
that you have a tendency
toward self-pity?

560
00:50:02,697 --> 00:50:04,528
No, you're the first.

561
00:50:04,598 --> 00:50:08,125
All right. Frank, I have
a friend up there, Roy Palmer.

562
00:50:08,202 --> 00:50:12,332
He's an administrative officer.
I'll speak with him.

563
00:50:12,406 --> 00:50:14,704
- Good. Thank you, sir.
- Good-bye, Frank.

564
00:50:14,775 --> 00:50:16,936
- God bless you.
- Right.

565
00:50:25,953 --> 00:50:28,581
<i>Frank, Captain McClain here.</i>

566
00:50:28,656 --> 00:50:30,749
Captain McClain. Could you
hold on a minute please, sir?

567
00:50:30,825 --> 00:50:32,258
<i>Sure.</i>

568
00:50:38,799 --> 00:50:41,233
Yeah. Sorry.

569
00:50:41,302 --> 00:50:43,236
I saw Inspector Palmer tonight...

570
00:50:43,304 --> 00:50:46,831
and he assures me the 7th Division
is as clean as a hound's tooth.

571
00:50:46,907 --> 00:50:49,307
His words, Frank.
"Clean as a hound's tooth."

572
00:50:50,144 --> 00:50:53,113
<i>I told him he was getting
a hardworking officer...</i>

573
00:50:53,180 --> 00:50:57,116
wears a beard, speaks Spanish and
would make a superb undercover man.

574
00:50:57,184 --> 00:50:58,446
He was delighted.

575
00:50:58,519 --> 00:51:02,512
That's good news, sir.
Thank you. Thank you very much.

576
00:51:02,590 --> 00:51:04,615
<i>Good-bye, Frank.
God bless.</i>

577
00:51:07,228 --> 00:51:09,822
When did you start doing that?

578
00:51:11,632 --> 00:51:13,930
McClain says that Palmer says...

579
00:51:14,001 --> 00:51:16,401
that the 7th is as clean
as a hound's tooth.

580
00:51:17,638 --> 00:51:20,630
Well, if that's true,
your problems are over.

581
00:51:25,846 --> 00:51:27,780
Plainclothes division.

582
00:51:29,617 --> 00:51:31,050
Upstairs.

583
00:51:42,029 --> 00:51:44,657
- How are you? Good to see you!
- All right.

584
00:51:44,732 --> 00:51:46,791
We heard you were
coming up here. Listen.

585
00:51:46,867 --> 00:51:49,995
Say hello to Nate Smith.
Frank Serpico.

586
00:51:50,071 --> 00:51:52,904
- Jamie Morales, Frank Serpico.
- Serpico?

587
00:51:53,974 --> 00:51:56,340
Hey, babe, you're gonna
love it up here. It's beautiful.

588
00:51:56,410 --> 00:51:58,469
Listen, take...
I'll see youse later, all right?

589
00:51:58,546 --> 00:52:00,912
Take a little ride with me.
Get the feel of the division.

590
00:52:00,981 --> 00:52:03,006
- Maybe I should check in first.
- Fuck that. Come on.

591
00:52:04,485 --> 00:52:08,251
<i>Deck the halls
with boughs of holly</i>

592
00:52:12,860 --> 00:52:16,523
Ten grand, Dallas...
if Minnesota. Right.

593
00:52:16,597 --> 00:52:18,292
Green Bay, 12 and a half at...

594
00:52:18,999 --> 00:52:22,298
You dumb fuck.
We told you this location's hot.

595
00:52:22,369 --> 00:52:24,394
We told you to stay the fuck
out of here.

596
00:52:24,472 --> 00:52:27,236
Keough, nobody told me.
Honest.

597
00:52:27,308 --> 00:52:29,367
Bullshit.

598
00:52:29,443 --> 00:52:31,206
Come on.
Let's take a walk.

599
00:52:31,278 --> 00:52:33,542
Hi, kid.
All right, a C-note apiece.

600
00:52:33,614 --> 00:52:37,675
No way. We got a complaint.
Right, Frank? Come on.

601
00:52:37,751 --> 00:52:39,946
All right.
Make it 200, Keough.

602
00:52:40,020 --> 00:52:42,853
Hey, what, are you getting cheap
in your old age, bambino?

603
00:52:42,923 --> 00:52:45,551
- Three.
- Three?

604
00:52:45,626 --> 00:52:47,287
You heard me.

605
00:52:48,362 --> 00:52:51,559
- All right, three.
- I'll make it a light one.

606
00:52:54,835 --> 00:52:58,498
- You wanna write this up?
- No, I'm gonna check in.

607
00:52:58,572 --> 00:53:00,506
Take the collar, Frank.
Get on the sheet.

608
00:53:00,574 --> 00:53:02,007
I better check in.

609
00:53:04,011 --> 00:53:07,276
We're gonna have
a little talk later, right?

610
00:53:10,751 --> 00:53:13,845
That dumb schmuck only came up with
two bills because I booked him?

611
00:53:16,724 --> 00:53:18,214
Here you go, Frank.

612
00:53:18,292 --> 00:53:20,886
It was your collar.
Keep it.

613
00:53:22,329 --> 00:53:24,854
I had a hunch
you weren't gonna take it.

614
00:53:26,033 --> 00:53:29,400
You know, Frankie, we got a call
about you from downtown.

615
00:53:29,470 --> 00:53:31,097
Now, I ain't sayin' who.

616
00:53:31,172 --> 00:53:33,834
They just said you couldn't
be trusted, you know?

617
00:53:34,909 --> 00:53:37,707
- Because I don't take money, right?
- Come on, Frank.

618
00:53:37,778 --> 00:53:40,269
Let's face it. Who can trust
a cop who don't take money?

619
00:53:41,248 --> 00:53:43,842
I mean, you are pretty weird,
you know, kid?

620
00:53:43,918 --> 00:53:46,682
And with that call, the guys
were gettin' a little worried.

621
00:53:46,754 --> 00:53:49,552
I told them you were okay.
I knew you from the old 21.

622
00:53:49,623 --> 00:53:52,956
You'd never hurt
another cop, right?

623
00:53:53,928 --> 00:53:56,954
You'd never hurt another cop,
would you, Frank?

624
00:53:57,031 --> 00:53:59,829
- That'd depend on what he did.
- That's the wrong answer, Frankie.

625
00:54:05,673 --> 00:54:07,402
We're not doing
anything bad here.

626
00:54:07,474 --> 00:54:10,136
We're skimming
a little gambling money.

627
00:54:10,211 --> 00:54:13,237
It's clean. It's not dope.
It hurts nobody.

628
00:54:13,314 --> 00:54:15,248
Come on, Frank.

629
00:54:15,316 --> 00:54:18,615
Gamblers are gentlemen, and
they're gonna operate anyhow, right?

630
00:54:18,686 --> 00:54:21,211
Look, Keough, you don't have to
explain yourself to me.

631
00:54:21,288 --> 00:54:24,416
Do what you got to do.
Want some tea?

632
00:54:24,491 --> 00:54:27,460
No, I don't like that shit.
I'll have a coffee, huh?

633
00:54:27,528 --> 00:54:30,156
What's the matter, Frank?
What are you worried about?

634
00:54:30,231 --> 00:54:33,564
Listen.
We don't go overboard here.

635
00:54:33,634 --> 00:54:35,625
We're not sloppy.
We're careful.

636
00:54:35,703 --> 00:54:39,002
The spicks, niggers, we bust them.
They operate so dumb and sloppy...

637
00:54:39,073 --> 00:54:41,166
they get your ass
in hot water every time.

638
00:54:41,242 --> 00:54:43,767
But the Italians, now,
that's a different story.

639
00:54:43,844 --> 00:54:47,075
They're men of their word.
They're reliable, Frankie.

640
00:54:47,147 --> 00:54:50,446
- You really got it analyzed.
- Fuckin' right I got it analyzed.

641
00:54:50,517 --> 00:54:52,212
It's worth it.

642
00:54:53,287 --> 00:54:55,778
You know how much
the nut's running now, Frankie?

643
00:54:57,891 --> 00:55:01,918
- No, I wouldn't know that.
- $800 a month.

644
00:55:01,996 --> 00:55:06,399
That's 800 clams every time your
girlfriend gets the curse tax free.

645
00:55:07,268 --> 00:55:10,260
Here's the beauty. You don't
get it for the first eight weeks...

646
00:55:10,337 --> 00:55:13,067
till the guys get to
know you and you're okay.

647
00:55:13,140 --> 00:55:15,768
But you don't lose, either, 'cause
you get it on the other end...

648
00:55:15,843 --> 00:55:18,573
when you leave the division.

649
00:55:18,646 --> 00:55:21,672
Frankie, it's like...
it's like severance pay.

650
00:55:23,284 --> 00:55:26,412
Think it over, all right?
In or out.

651
00:55:29,223 --> 00:55:31,783
Look at me. I'm shaking.

652
00:55:35,863 --> 00:55:38,229
All my life I wanted
to be a cop, you know?

653
00:55:38,299 --> 00:55:40,665
It's like I can remember
nothing else.

654
00:55:44,305 --> 00:55:46,330
I remember this one time...

655
00:55:47,741 --> 00:55:49,675
there was...

656
00:55:49,743 --> 00:55:52,268
Somethin' happened.
A domestic argument or somethin'.

657
00:55:52,346 --> 00:55:54,280
Somebody stabbed somebody.

658
00:55:55,316 --> 00:55:57,716
And...

659
00:55:57,785 --> 00:56:00,345
there was this crowd
around this tenement.

660
00:56:01,422 --> 00:56:04,789
I must have been nine,
ten years old. I was this big.

661
00:56:04,858 --> 00:56:06,792
I went over to see
what was going on.

662
00:56:06,860 --> 00:56:10,057
I noticed the red light
goin' around and around...

663
00:56:10,130 --> 00:56:12,564
all these people,
and I couldn't see.

664
00:56:13,634 --> 00:56:17,126
I kept saying, "Do you know
what's goin' on? Do you know?"

665
00:56:17,204 --> 00:56:19,365
Nobody knew.

666
00:56:19,440 --> 00:56:22,637
It was like a big mystery
behind that...

667
00:56:22,710 --> 00:56:24,337
that crowd there.

668
00:56:25,412 --> 00:56:27,846
All of a sudden...

669
00:56:27,915 --> 00:56:29,974
the crowd just parted...

670
00:56:30,050 --> 00:56:32,416
like the Red Sea, you see?

671
00:56:32,486 --> 00:56:36,047
And there were these guys
in blue, and I said...

672
00:56:36,123 --> 00:56:37,954
"They know."

673
00:56:39,026 --> 00:56:41,996
What do they know?
What do they know?

674
00:56:47,267 --> 00:56:49,462
It's amazing.

675
00:56:49,536 --> 00:56:51,504
It's incredible...

676
00:56:52,573 --> 00:56:55,542
but I feel like a criminal
'cause I don't take money.

677
00:56:59,613 --> 00:57:02,138
You get so tense
when you talk about it.

678
00:57:02,216 --> 00:57:03,649
I wonder why.

679
00:57:03,717 --> 00:57:05,309
Come here.

680
00:57:09,490 --> 00:57:11,355
- Right there.
- Here?

681
00:57:13,093 --> 00:57:16,426
I'm gonna ask you
a question, okay?

682
00:57:16,497 --> 00:57:18,795
Do you like cops?

683
00:57:18,866 --> 00:57:20,800
You're my first.

684
00:57:22,469 --> 00:57:25,870
No, I mean all this shit I've been
telling you. Do you believe it?

685
00:57:25,939 --> 00:57:27,531
Why not?

686
00:57:28,942 --> 00:57:31,502
- Does it shock you?
- Not much.

687
00:57:32,579 --> 00:57:35,207
What's the matter with me?

688
00:57:35,282 --> 00:57:37,375
Everybody knows about cops.

689
00:57:38,452 --> 00:57:41,080
Did you ever hear the story
of the wise king?

690
00:57:41,155 --> 00:57:44,318
Nope, but I got the feeling
I'm gonna hear it.

691
00:57:45,392 --> 00:57:49,829
Well, there was this king,
and he ruled over his kingdom.

692
00:57:49,897 --> 00:57:53,298
Right in the middle of the kingdom
there was a well.

693
00:57:53,367 --> 00:57:55,358
That's where everybody drank.

694
00:57:55,436 --> 00:57:59,065
One night,
this witch came along...

695
00:57:59,139 --> 00:58:01,073
and she poisoned the well.

696
00:58:02,176 --> 00:58:05,304
And the next day, everybody drank
from it except the king...

697
00:58:05,379 --> 00:58:07,438
and they all went crazy.

698
00:58:07,514 --> 00:58:09,812
They got together
in the street and they said...

699
00:58:09,883 --> 00:58:12,852
"We got to get rid of the king,
'cause the king is mad."

700
00:58:15,189 --> 00:58:18,420
And then that night, he went down
and he drank from the well.

701
00:58:18,492 --> 00:58:21,290
And the next day
all the people rejoiced...

702
00:58:21,361 --> 00:58:25,457
because their king
had regained his reason.

703
00:58:29,203 --> 00:58:31,137
I think you're trying
to tell me somethin'.

704
00:58:31,205 --> 00:58:33,036
- Me?
- Yeah.

705
00:58:35,075 --> 00:58:37,543
Hey, Frank, I want you
to say hello to somebody.

706
00:58:37,611 --> 00:58:41,547
- Drop your cocks and grab your socks!
- What the fuck is this?

707
00:58:43,250 --> 00:58:46,014
Frank Serpico,
say hello to Don Rubello.

708
00:58:46,086 --> 00:58:48,179
- He's gonna be your new partner.
- How you doin'?

709
00:58:49,756 --> 00:58:53,658
If you don't want to work with this
fucking nut for some reason, man...

710
00:58:53,727 --> 00:58:56,696
I'll buddy up with him,
all right?

711
00:58:56,763 --> 00:58:59,061
And go through all that crap
changing assignments?

712
00:58:59,133 --> 00:59:01,226
No. We'll be okay.

713
00:59:01,301 --> 00:59:03,132
<i>We're paisans, huh?</i>

714
00:59:06,073 --> 00:59:08,200
- What's with the fucking mouse?
- It's my partner.

715
00:59:08,275 --> 00:59:11,039
- Partner?
- He's specially trained, you know?

716
00:59:11,111 --> 00:59:14,239
He goes to track down heroin.

717
00:59:14,314 --> 00:59:17,010
Let him loose, goes into the hole,
picks it up, brings it back...

718
00:59:17,084 --> 00:59:19,518
sniffs it out,
brings it to you.

719
00:59:21,255 --> 00:59:23,985
- Yeah. I heard of that.
- You heard of that?

720
00:59:27,861 --> 00:59:30,989
This guy I'm looking for,
Vernon...

721
00:59:31,064 --> 00:59:34,124
He's a numbers collector who ain't
been meeting his obligations.

722
00:59:35,602 --> 00:59:39,129
He won't be hard to spot.
He's a mover. This is prime time.

723
00:59:42,676 --> 00:59:46,373
Since we're partners,
you gotta know the situation.

724
00:59:46,446 --> 00:59:50,507
Straight off.
I collect for the division...

